# Ticket-Flow — ticket-driven workflow ({{backend.displayName}})

This project follows a five-phase, ticket-driven workflow. **Recognize the user's intent from normal conversation and run the matching phase — they do _not_ need to type the slash command.** Each phase's full procedure lives in the linked file; open it and follow it. The slash command is just a shortcut to the same procedure.

- **Find the next ticket** — when the user asks what to work on, what's next, what's in the backlog, or which ticket to pick up. → {{skillRef "next-ticket"}}
- **Describe / plan a ticket** — when the user wants a ticket turned into product behavior, acceptance criteria, and an execution plan, or says things like "plan {{eg.prefixUpper}}-123", "break this ticket down", "what's the plan for this". → {{skillRef "describe-ticket"}}
- **Execute a ticket** — when the user wants to build a planned ticket or ship it (test gate → push → PR → move to {{state "inReview"}}): "build {{eg.prefixUpper}}-123", "implement this ticket", "start coding it", "ship it", "open a PR". → {{skillRef "execute-ticket"}}
- **Review a ticket** — when the user wants the ticket's PR reviewed or checked against its acceptance criteria: "review the PR", "is {{eg.prefixUpper}}-123 ready", "does this meet the criteria". → {{skillRef "review-ticket"}}
- **Fix a ticket's PR feedback** — when the user wants to act on review comments or a failing/blocked PR: "fix the review comments", "address the PR feedback", "fix the failing CI on {{eg.prefixUpper}}-123". → {{skillRef "fix-ticket"}}
- **Merge a ticket** — when the user wants to land/merge reviewed work and close out: "merge it", "land {{eg.prefixUpper}}-123", "close out the ticket". → {{skillRef "merge-ticket"}}

**Lifecycle order:** next → describe → execute → review → merge, with **fix** looping back from review/merge whenever the PR has open comments or red CI. The phases are idempotent and resumable: if an earlier phase was skipped, the later one falls back gracefully (e.g. execute cuts the branch if describe never ran). When the intent is ambiguous, ask which phase the user means before acting.

## Sub-agents & multiple tickets

- The lifecycle applies **per ticket**, regardless of who executes: N tickets in flight = N work artifacts, N branches, N state transitions — never a shared or skipped trail.
- Delegating a phase to a sub-agent does not skip that phase's procedure. Sub-agents return data; the orchestrator performs and verifies every backend write (artifact upsert, comments, state moves, PR links) when the delegated work returns — or embeds the phase's exact write procedure in the sub-agent's prompt and verifies the writes landed afterwards.
- Work tickets in dependency order (Blocked-by first) and summarize progress to the user at each ticket boundary.
